CONTENT ANGLE SELECTION (FALLBACK — used if Step Zero found no hype)
═══════════════════════════════════
Only choose topics that can be clearly shown through short visual clips or strong still images with obvious action, emotion, or movement.

Before choosing a topic, pick a random number from one to four. State the number first.

one → surprising micro-detail (the "wait-WHAT" soap pattern — see below)
two → mind-blowing record or stat
three → iconic moment / the story behind it (lore)
four → news or recent development (timely — extra source + recency rules apply)

Follow the selected angle. Focus on ONE specific idea, not a broad topic.

GOOD example: why a boxing "ring" is called a ring even though it is square
BAD example: the history of boxing

═══════════════════════════════════
WHAT MAKES A FACT GOOD (READ FIRST)
═══════════════════════════════════
The target is NOT "most obscure." The target is "makes a viewer say wait, WHAT?"

Obscurity is welcome — but ONLY when it raises the reaction. A rare-but-boring fact is worse than a mid-rarity fascinating one.

The ideal fact pattern (the "soap pattern"):
A small, concrete, almost ordinary detail (a habit, an object, a hidden rule, a number, a backstory) attached to a famous athlete, fight, club, or moment — where the real, verifiable answer is funnier, stranger, or bigger than expected.

Reference example (for calibration only — match the FLAVOR, not this exact fact):
"Brazilian goalkeeper Rogério Ceni scored over one hundred career goals — more than many strikers." → famous-enough subject, concrete record, zero backstory needed, instant 'wait WHAT?'. THIS is the level to aim for.

THE THREE TRAITS EVERY WINNING FACT SHARES (all three required):
- CONCRETE: a physical, numerical, or behavioral detail you could picture or verify — not an opinion or vibe.
- FAMOUS ANCHOR: it attaches to something a casual fan already knows. Surprise lands harder on familiar ground.
- ZERO-LECTURE: the surprise lands in one sentence, with no long backstory needed first.

NOTE: Even when anchored to a hot/hype event, the fact must still follow the soap pattern — a concrete micro-detail, not a results recap.

═══════════════════════════════════
TOPIC DISCOVERY PROTOCOL (MANDATORY)
═══════════════════════════════════
Generate FIVE candidate ideas.
- If Step Zero found hype: all five candidates must connect to that hot event.
- If using the fallback wheel: all five must fit the chosen angle.

Each idea must name a SPECIFIC source anchor at this stage (official stat database, named match/fight + date, reputable report, documented interview, record body) — vague ideas are discarded immediately.

DIVERSITY RULE: the five candidates must cover at least THREE different subjects (different athletes / fights / clubs / eras). Do not generate five ideas all about the same superstar. The freshest "wait WHAT" facts hide outside the obvious names. (When anchored to a single hot event, vary the angle within it instead — different people, details, or stats inside that event.)

For each candidate assign ONE score only:

WAIT-WHAT SCORE (one–five):
one → "ok, neat"
two → "mildly interesting"
three → "huh, I didn't know that"
four → "oh that's actually wild"
five → "wait, WHAT? — I want to tell someone right now"

A fact must score FOUR or higher to be used.

KILL TEST — automatically reject a candidate if it is:
- well-known to most fans (no surprise)
- a DRY number with no story (a plain salary, a net worth, a basic "most goals/titles" list everyone already knows)
- an opinion or debate dressed as a fact (GOAT takes, "best ever", "most skilful")
- requires a long backstory before the surprise lands
- a stat you cannot date or verify, or that may already be out of date
- any fact whose source you could not open and read this session (memory-only citations are BANNED — see Verification Protocol)
- more than forty percent similar to anything in the USED VIDEOS LIST

BANNED OVERSATURATED PATTERNS (recycled to death — never pick these):
Messi-vs-Ronaldo GOAT debates; "Ronaldo doesn't get tattoos because he donates blood"; generic richest-athlete / highest-paid / net-worth lists; Mayweather "fifty and zero" with no new angle; Mike Tyson ear bite; McGregor whiskey / "billi" strut; "this player's release clause was…" with no twist; basic most-goals / most-titles rankings; transfer-fee record lists everyone has seen. F1 specifically: "drivers lose several kilos every race"; "the halo saved a life" clip with no new angle; DRS-explained; the twenty twenty-one Abu Dhabi finish; driver-salary lists; "G-force in a corner" with no twist.

Pick the highest-scoring surviving candidate.
If no candidate scores four or higher, generate five NEW ideas.

═══════════════════════════════════
DUPLICATE DETECTION RULE
═══════════════════════════════════
Discard a topic if it matches any USED VIDEOS LIST entry on ANY of these:
- same athlete + same detail / record / habit
- same record or stat explained with different words
- same match/fight/moment reworded
- same "what does X / why does X" framing about the same subject

Example:
Existing: why ronaldo jumps so high for headers
