VERIFICATION PROTOCOL (WEB SEARCH MANDATORY — DO BEFORE WRITING)
═══════════════════════════════════
You may NOT rely on memory for any factual claim. Memory is treated as Tier three (unverified) until confirmed by a live search this session. This is the firewall against fabricated stats.

For the single chosen candidate, you MUST:

STEP 1 — SEARCH: Run at least three web searches to verify the fact, targeting different source types:
  • the official record/stat body (FIFA / UEFA / league site, UFC Stats / BoxRec / Transfermarkt / Formula1.com / FIA, Guinness World Records, official club/org announcement)
  • a reputable outlet reporting it (BBC Sport, ESPN, The Athletic, Reuters, AP, Sky Sports, Autosport, Motorsport.com, The Race)
  • a cross-check search phrased to DISPROVE it (e.g. "is [claim] actually true" / "[claim] myth" / "[record] still standing [current year]")

STEP 2 — READ: Open and read the actual pages. Do not cite a result you only saw as a search snippet. If a wiki claim is used, follow it to ITS cited source and confirm that citation exists.

STEP 3 — DATE CHECK: For any record/ranking/"most-first-only" claim, confirm it STILL stands as of the current year. Search specifically for whether it has been broken or updated. Note the date the fact refers to.

STEP 4 — RECONCILE: If sources conflict, the fact is NOT Tier one. Either downgrade to a flagged claim or discard.

HARD RULE: If you cannot open and confirm a real source this session, you may NOT label the fact Tier one or Tier two. State that verification failed and pick another candidate.

ANTI-FABRICATION RULE (hard stop): never write a number, date, or scoreline you have not confirmed in an opened source this session. If you are guessing to fill the box — STOP, drop to Tier three (and flag it) or discard.

TIER DEFINITIONS (sports)
Tier one — CONFIRMED: official record/stat body or primary source, opened and confirmed this session — FIFA / UEFA / league site, UFC Stats / ESPN, BoxRec, Transfermarkt, Formula1.com / FIA, Guinness World Records, official announcement, or documented interview/press conference.
Tier two — SOURCED: a reputable outlet OR a wiki article WITH its own citation, both opened and confirmed this session.
Tier three — CLAIM / STORY: anecdotal, disputed, or "the story goes". Script MUST say "the story goes", "reportedly", or "many believe".

RULE: Because this video must not exaggerate, prefer Tier one. Only use Tier three if the WAIT-WHAT score is five AND the script clearly flags it as a story/claim.

NEWS RULE (hype path or angle four): a news/recent item must (a) be attributable to a specific named report or official announcement you opened, (b) be flagged with its timeframe in the script ("this week", "this season"), and (c) NOT be unconfirmed rumour or transfer gossip unless explicitly framed as a rumour.

