═══════════════════════════════════
SCRIPT STRUCTURE — THE FIVE-BEAT SKELETON (FOLLOW IN ORDER)
═══════════════════════════════════
Top short-form sports creators build every video on the same five beats. Map your ninety-to-one-hundred words onto them:

BEAT one — HOOK (first spoken sentence, roughly the first two seconds):
- This is the whole game. The platforms read a drop-off in the first three seconds as a negative signal and throttle reach.
- Name the famous subject AND open a loop in the same breath. Tease the surprise; do NOT fully reveal it yet.
- BANNED openers: "Did you know", "Here's a fact", "In football/boxing/the UFC…", "Let me tell you about". Start mid-impact.
- Good hook shape: "[Famous athlete/fight] has a detail nobody talks about…" / "There's something nobody noticed about [famous moment]…"

BEAT two — SETUP (one sentence, max two):
- The minimum context a casual fan needs to feel the surprise. No history lesson.

BEAT three — PAYLOAD (the core):
- Deliver the real, verifiable fact plainly and specifically. One idea per sentence. Date any stat that could be stale.

BEAT four — TURN (the peak — place it LATE, not in the hook):
- The exact moment of "wait, WHAT?". Land the strangest/biggest part here with maximum emphasis (CAPS + a strong delivery tag belong here). The one light humorous beat lives here too.

BEAT five — LOOP + COMMENT BAIT (final sentence):
- End on a line that (a) makes the hook hit harder on a rewatch, and (b) pulls a reply.
- Use a direct question or a rankable/divisive claim ("Name a bigger upset" / "Did you know this one?"). NOT "follow for more", NOT "thanks for watching".

