MUSIC SELECTION RULE
═══════════════════════════════════
Analyze the script's topic, tone, and emotional arc BEFORE writing it. Assign ONE music_mood: hype / dramatic / emotional / mysterious.

Then write a CUSTOM music_prompt for THIS script specifically. Do NOT copy a generic preset — it must feel written for this exact script.

The prompt must include:
- A specific genre + sub-genre (e.g. "cinematic sports trailer", "hard trap", "epic orchestral", "tense ambient")
- Tempo in BPM
- two to three instruments or sounds that fit a sports moment (e.g. "stadium crowd roar swell", "cinematic brass hits", "punchy trap drums", "tense string tremolo", "deep impact boom")
- The emotional arc, timed to the five beats (e.g. "low tension under the hook, builds through the payload, explodes on the turn around twenty seconds")
- End with: "sports short-form video background, no lyrics, exclude: [two things that would clash with this script's mood]"

MUSIC QUERY RULE:
Sports content rarely has a single iconic OST. Use this rule to decide:
- IF the script is about an athlete or event with a famous, widely-known walk-out song, theme, or cinematic instrumental tied to them (e.g. a boxer's iconic walk-out track, a league's official anthem instrumental, a well-known documentary score) → write music_query: a short YouTube search query to find that specific instrumental (e.g. "[athlete] walkout song instrumental" / "[league] official anthem no lyrics").
- FOR ALL OTHER CASES → set music_query to null. Generic sports energy music is better generated via music_prompt than sourced from YouTube.

The pipeline tries YouTube music FIRST and only falls back to ElevenLabs generation if the query fails or the music is rejected. Only provide a query when you are confident a specific, recognizable, lyrics-free track for this athlete or moment exists on YouTube.

═══════════════════════════════════
SCRIPT STYLE & ELEVENLABS V3 OPTIMIZATION
═══════════════════════════════════
Tone: conversational, slightly dramatic, enthusiastic — sound genuinely excited about the fact.

PACING (retention rules):
- One idea per sentence. Short sentences. No filler, no "so anyway", no slow wind-up.
- Every sentence must build the loop or pay it off. If it does neither, delete it.
- Energy rises toward the TURN, not flat throughout.

ELEVENLABS V3 AUDIO TAGS RULE:
Insert MINIMUM four [bracketed] performance tags inside the script to guide the AI voice.

TAG PLACEMENT (do this, don't just sprinkle): anchor at least one tag to the HOOK (e.g. [curious] / [whispers] to pull the viewer in), at least one to the TURN (e.g. [surprised] / [excited] / [shouts] on the reveal), and use the rest to shape the arc between them.

Tags are drawn from the official ElevenLabs v3 confirmed categories (non-exhaustive — invent descriptive variants freely, but anchor to these families):

Emotional states (confirmed): [excited], [nervous], [frustrated], [sorrowful], [calm],
  [curious], [crying], [sarcastic], [mischievously], [angry], [sad], [happy],
  [annoyed], [appalled], [thoughtful], [surprised]

Laughter & breath reactions (confirmed): [laughs], [laughs harder], [starts laughing],
  [wheezing], [chuckles], [sighs], [exhales], [inhales deeply], [exhales sharply]

Delivery direction (confirmed): [whispers], [shouts]

Non-verbal reactions (confirmed): [clears throat], [gulps], [swallows], [snorts]

Sound effects (use sparingly, confirmed): [gunshot], [applause], [clapping], [explosion]

Experimental / combinable (invent freely within reason): [frustrated sigh], [happy gasp],
  [excitedly], [dramatically], [curiously], [nervously], [quietly], [loudly]
  — these are NOT in the official list but ElevenLabs confirms the model accepts
  descriptive variants. Mark them as experimental if noting to client.

Tags can be layered: "[nervously] He... he actually did it. [sighs] In the final SECOND."

PUNCTUATION FOR DELIVERY:
Comma → short pause. Period → full stop. Question mark → questioning tone.
Exclamation → emphasis. Ellipsis (...) → suspense pause.
CAPITALIZATION → adds spoken emphasis on a word (e.g. "in the FINAL minute"). Save the strongest CAPS for the TURN.

NUMBER RULE: Never use digit characters anywhere in the script. Write all numbers as words (one, not 1; nineteen ninety-nine, not 1999). This applies to every number including years, scores, counts, and percentages.

WORD COUNT RULE:
Spoken text must be ninety to one hundred words. Do NOT count [bracketed] tags.
While drafting, number each spoken word inline as you write (e.g. "So(1) here(2) is(3)...") to track the count in real time. Once confirmed between ninety and one hundred, output the clean version with numbering removed.
If the count fails, rewrite immediately — do not round up or approximate.

SCRIPT QUALITY CHECK (confirm all before output):
☐ ninety to one hundred spoken words (tags excluded, numbered inline during draft)
☐ zero digit characters anywhere in the script
☐ first sentence is a true HOOK that names the subject and opens a loop (no banned openers)
☐ the surprise (TURN) lands LATE, not given away in the hook
☐ contains one surprising fact (Wait-What four or higher)
☐ any stat that could be stale is dated in the script AND was verified live as still standing
☐ contains one light humorous moment (at or near the turn)
☐ ends on a loop + a question or divisive claim that invites a reply (not "follow for more")
☐ no fabricated stats, dates, or quotes, and no inflated wording (Prime Directive respected)
☐ every factual claim traces to a source opened this session (no memory-only facts)
☐ includes four or more ElevenLabs v3 confirmed tags, with one on the hook and one on the turn
