═══════════════════════════════════
VISUAL CLIP STRATEGY (SPORTS — COPYRIGHT-AWARE)
═══════════════════════════════════

⚠️ COPYRIGHT REALITY (READ FIRST):
Sports rights-holders are far more aggressive than anime studios. UEFA, the Premier League, the UFC, and Formula One (FOM / Liberty Media) issue takedowns and Content ID claims even on short, transformative edits — full match / round / fight / race action is the single most-struck content online.
Source priority, safest first:
1) Official org/club/promotion uploads and press materials (what THEY chose to publish).
2) Non-match footage: press conferences, weigh-ins, open workouts, walkouts, interviews, trophy lifts, training-ground / "mic'd up" clips, players' own social posts.
3) Still images + motion (Ken Burns) — for the riskiest leagues, photos avoid video Content ID entirely.
4) Licensed stock or Creative-Commons b-roll (stadium exteriors, generic crowd, gloves/ball close-ups) for safe filler.
Rules: keep any borrowed action clip very short; NEVER post a full goal/round/fight; always layer voiceover + on-screen text + edits (transformation); expect claims and don't build a channel on one risky clip. This is not legal advice.

── SCENE QUERY (for Gemini / visual search) ──────────────────
scene_query is for an AI visual search tool (e.g. Gemini) to find the single best-matching moment. It is NOT a YouTube search query.

Write scene_query as a pure physical description of what the screen looks like:
- Describe the athlete's appearance, kit/shorts/gloves colours, the venue, and key objects
- Describe kinetic action or emotion: sprinting, a free-kick strike, a knockdown, arms raised, a stare-down, a crowd erupting, a car sliding through a corner, a lightning pit stop, champagne on the podium
- No jargon — translate into visuals (e.g. "a goalkeeper running the length of the pitch to take a free kick", not "Ceni's free-kick record")
- Anchor to the most visually strong moment the script references (ideally one that exists in OFFICIAL or PRESS/NON-MATCH footage, given the copyright reality)
- If the fact has no single defining clip (a record or stat), describe the most iconic representative image of that athlete/moment
- If the script references a specific moment, the scene_query must match that exact moment — do not generalize

── YOUTUBE QUERIES (for sourcing footage) ────────────────
Generate exactly six YouTube queries. Write them the way a real fan types into the YouTube search bar — short, natural, casual. Two to six words. NOT keyword-stuffed. Each must hit a DIFFERENT pool, and given the copyright reality, lean toward SAFE pools (official, press, stills, b-roll) over live action.

RULES FOR NATURAL QUERIES:
- Use the words fans and uploaders actually put in titles: the athlete's name, "press conference", "interview", "weigh in", "walkout", "training", "highlights", "documentary", the event name.
- Drop jargon real uploaders never write: avoid "isolated footage", "no commentary", "content ID safe", "broadcast feed".
- Lead with the most recognizable name: athlete, event, or the iconic moment.
- One subject per query set: if the script is about a specific moment, every query chases THAT moment in different words.
- Each of the six must hit a DIFFERENT pool, not reword the same search.

THE SIX ANGLES (natural phrasing, safe pools first):

Query one — OFFICIAL ORG / LEAGUE
What the rights-holder published themselves (lowest strike risk).
e.g. "[athlete] [event] official" / "UFC [fighter] official"

Query two — PRESS CONFERENCE / WEIGH-IN / INTERVIEW
Faces, quotes, emotion — widely shared, lower strike risk.
e.g. "[athlete] press conference" / "[fighter] weigh in" / "[athlete] interview"

Query three — TRAINING / BEHIND THE SCENES
Off-broadcast footage of the subject.
e.g. "[athlete] training" / "[athlete] mic'd up" / "[club] behind the scenes"

Query four — PHOTOS / STILLS / GRAPHIC
A non-video pool that dodges video Content ID.
e.g. "[athlete] [moment] photo" / "[record] stat graphic"

Query five — DOCUMENTARY / ARCHIVE / ON THIS DAY
Retrospective and classic-footage pool — different from current uploads.
e.g. "[moment] documentary" / "[athlete] on this day" / "[era] retro"

Query six — STOCK / B-ROLL
Safe filler under the hook and between cuts.
e.g. "[sport] stadium b roll" / "[equipment] stock footage" / "crowd cheering stock"

SCENE ACCURACY RULE: If the script references a specific moment, all six queries must chase that exact moment — not the athlete in general.

DO NOT generate queries that are slight rephrasings of the same idea. Each must point to a genuinely different pool.

OUTPUT: Replace every bracket with real athlete/event/moment names before outputting. No leftover brackets.

